^B@2 ^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The modern approach is to allow "free bids" with fewer values than previously. Basically, the approach over a takeout double is, if responder has something useful to say, he/she should say it. This means, for example, if responder has 8 or more points, or a suit worth mentioning even with only 6 points, he/she should make a bid. A suit worth mentioning is either a 5 card suit or a good 4 card suit. In this case, hearts, with 2 honors, qualifies. Note that Marge did not redouble, so Kia should realize she has less than 10 points.|
PG| ***** 103 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2 ^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Obviously, Marge could not make a negative double, since West doubled. But had the auction gone 1C-1D, even then, Marge should bid 1H rather than making a negative double. The negative double in that case should show both majors.|
PG| ***** 104 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2 ^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The problem case for negative doubles is when it goes 1D-2C. There a negative double should show both majors, but needs to be a little flexible. With long spades and a weak hand, responder can make a negative double and then correct 2H to 2S, to show a weak hand with spades. (The same is not true with long hearts, because correcting 2S to 3H requires going to the 3 level.) Also, if responder has one major and club support, she can also make a negative double, correcting the wrong major to 3C. Finally, with 4-3, if responder has a good 3-card major and is willing to play in a 4-3 fit, she can make a negative double.|
PG| ***** 105 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2 ^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to what Kia should do over 3D. More often than not, Marge will have a 5 card suit. So Kia should assume that is the case and bid 3H, presuming a 9 card fit. In this case, that turns out to not be the case, but 3H happens to make anyway.|
